09363nam a22011895i 9781978818453DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20202021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97819788184537 a10.36019/97819788184532doi  a(DE-B1597)574706  a(OCoLC)1196171805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aEDU0000002bisacsh04a378.1/99097322304aThe Synergistic Classroom :bInterdisciplinary Teaching in the Small College Setting /ced. by Corey Campion, Aaron Angello. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2020] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (228 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: -- tPart I Teaching across the Disciplines -- t1 The Anxiety of Interdisciplinary Teaching -- t2 Challenging the Discipline: -- t3 More Than Just Another Core Class: -- t4 Breaking Boundaries: -- t5 Interdisciplinary Interactivity: -- t6 Honeybees and the Transdisciplinary Classroom: -- tPart II Programming across the Disciplines -- t7 Learning, Leading, and Succeeding: -- t8 Why Can’t It Be Both?: -- t9 From Chemistry to History to Psychology: -- t10 Creating a “Space of Appearance” through the Rollins Foundations in the Liberal Arts Program -- t11 Flipping the Humanities Back into Mathematics -- t12 Arts in the Laboratory: -- tPart III Exploring across the Disciplines -- t13 Science and Cultural Competence: -- t14 Authenticity and Empathy in Education: -- t15 Experiential Learning in the Rural, Small College Setting: -- t16 “Hold My Piña Colada”: -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmong the many challenges confronting the liberal arts today is a fundamental disconnect between the curricula that many institutions offer and the training that many students need. Discipline-specific models of teaching and learning can underprepare students for the kinds of interdisciplinary collaboration that employers now expect. Although aware of these expectations and the need for change, many small colleges and universities have struggled to translate interdisciplinarity into programs and curricula that better serve today’s students. Written by faculty engaged in the design and delivery of interdisciplinary courses, programs, and experiential learning opportunities in the small college setting, The Synergistic Classroom addresses the many ways faculty can leverage their institutions' small size and openness to pedagogical experimentation to overcome the challenges of limited institutional resources and enrollment concerns and better prepare students for life and work in the twenty-first century. Taken together, the contributions in this volume invite reflection on a variety of important issues that attend the work of small college faculty committed to expanding student learning across disciplinary boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aEducation, HigherxCurriculazUnited States. 0aInterdisciplinary approach in educationzUnited States. 0aSmall collegeszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aCorey Campion, associate professor, history, global studies, director, master, Arts, humanities program, Hood College, Frederick, Maryland, Aaron Angello, Sophie. M. Libman, Education, Teaching Methods, Materials, Humanities, Teacher, Student Mentoring, liberal arts, Learning, Students, interdisciplinary, Collaboration, Synergistic Classroom, small college faculty, 20th Century.1 aAngello, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAngello, Aaron, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAustin, Allan W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarcenas-Moor